    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-06T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-06T14:00:00-05:00" n="464"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d464">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/202</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-06T19:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 6, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 6, 4.57 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8917. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 235. Your 6709, State Department February 27. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName> informs me the War
                    Cabinet have approved the proposal to give the Dutch until Monday next to agree
                    to the definite tonnage agreement in consideration for which Holland shall be
                    furnished 100,000 tons of bread grains, and failure acceptance of this that all
                    Dutch boats should be requisitioned. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName> informs me that he has
                    communicated to their British Chargé d’Affaires to postpone Dutch sailing. Have
                    asked the French to do likewise. I understand that nine Dutch boats have left
                    American ports under <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi;</hi> if so, please give us
                    the names and destinations. It is suggested that they should be kept track of to
                    prevent their escaping in cases of requisition.</p>
                <p>An intercepted cable from the Dutch Foreign Office at The Hague to the Dutch
                    Consul at Baltimore inquires the date and hour of sailing, the date and hour of
                    arrival last year of some 21 Dutch boats. Whilst this may be for statistical
                    purposes, it may be significant-Could you state where steamship <hi
                        rend="italic">Wieldrecht</hi> is now located?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
